rs and artisans and that many had to turn to and rely on the state for their livelihoods. The major themes of Upper Canada's history, from war and rebellion to immigration and settlement, are well-documented. In Duty Bound fleshes out the lives of ordinary people in Upper Canada and clarifies how several branches of government worked for, or against, the interests of the population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMenxGovernment policyxHistoryxOntario. 0aMenxGovernment policyzOntarioxHistory. 0aMenxSocial conditionsxOntario. 0aMenzOntarioxSocial conditions. 0aWomenxGovernment policyxOntario. 0aWomenxGovernment policyzOntario. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxOntario. 0aWomenzOntarioxSocial conditions. 0aWorking classxGovernment policyxHistoryxOntario. 0aWorking classxGovernment policyzOntarioxHistory. 0aWorking classxSocial conditionsxOntario. 0aWorking classzOntarioxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358963640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773589636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773589636/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles